Darrin Camilleri
March 23 at 7:06 PM ·

Huge thanks to New Boston Huron School District and Grosse Ile Township Schools for their donations of over 10,000 pairs of gloves, nearly 1000 masks, over 200 safety goggles, and boxes of sanitizer to Beaumont Health and Henry Ford Health System.

Also shoutout to some of my constituents who answered the call!

I dropped off this supplies on their behalf today. I’ll be going to Woodhaven schools and Gibraltar schools tomorrow for more.

#DownriverStrong

post_text: Mrs. Anton and Mrs. Metzger’s health science students participated in a simulation lab at St. Vincent Mercy Health Center, followed by an anatomy cadaver lab at the University of Toledo. Students assisted in a simulated “birth” as well as CPR, and were able to connect the academic knowledge learned in class regarding human anatomy and physiology.
text: Mrs. Anton and Mrs. Metzger’s health science students participated in a simulation lab at St. Vincent Mercy Health Center, followed by an anatomy cadaver lab at the University of Toledo. Students assisted in a simulated “birth” as well as CPR, and were able to connect the academic knowledge learned in class regarding human anatomy and physiology.

Are you interested in being part of our revised five year Strategic Plan? Click the link below to find out how to be part of this collaborative process!

https://bit.ly/2UFJd9y

---

Strategic Planning is the process of determining what an organization wants to be at some point in the future, and how it will get there. In the current environment where school are challenged to do more with scare resources, planning for the future is more important than ever. An effective strategic planning process results in stakeholders focusing on critical priorities that will meet the mission of a quality educational program for all students.

DCTC health science classes hosted 9th grade students from area schools. The 12th grade students were teaching the 9th grade students about skills they learned in class. Some of these skills were CPR, making an occupied hospital bed, isolation procedures, oral temperatures, and teamwork skills

post_text:
Grosse Ile Township Schools is in the process of implementing a new mass messaging system - SchoolMessenger. This system will send automated push notifications to your preferred device, e-mail or phone number with our customized application. This app will be available in the coming weeks via the App Store (Apple) and Google Play (Android) for free.

While we finish our implementation (ETA: 8/15/2019) we will be using our website (gischools.org) and social media to post updates. This includes material that would typically be included in our Friday backpack fliers until our new system is up and running.

Once our implementation is closer to completion, we will be sharing instructions on how to sign up and activate your accounts along with additional information.

Interested in learning more about SchoolMessenger? Feel free to visit their website at www.schoolmessenger.com.

post_text: GIHS head to Quito, Ecuador. First day visit to Yunguilla, a sustainable community in the cloud forest. They are running restaurant with all organic food from their huge garden, making cohita cheese and 4 jellies...lunch was delicious. Then we went to the Intinan Solar Museum and witnessed natural forces at work near the equator. Yes, the water flows in different directions, depending on what hemisphere you are in or if you are standing on the equator.

post_text:
Hello GIMS Parents,

Island Girl Scout Troop 40325 is hosting a stuffed animal drive for SAFE, Stuffed Animals for Emergencies.

Safe is an organization that collects stuffed animals and gives them to kids who have been through a natural disaster, are in the hospital or have been through a traumatic experience.

If you could send your GIMS student with new or gently used stuffed animals, we would greatly appreciate it.

The homeroom that brings the most amount of stuffed animals will receive a donut treat!

post_text: Strive for Safer Driving (S4SD by Ford) and the Downriver Distracted Driving Awareness Program (brought to Grosse Ile by Beaumont Hospital, Trenton) worked together to bring a distracted driving program that is aimed to reduce traffic accidents due to distracted or impaired driving. Students participated in various safe-driving events that taught them how to avoid distracted driving. The events included listening to speeches by a judge, a insurance agent. and two police officers along with outside activities aimed to create good driving habits.

post_text:
Spanish 4 students are working on creating poetry to expand vocabulary and find sounds that correspond to each other.

Here's a sampling from juniors Maddie Miller and Abbey Naso with their translations.

La Playa
es una casa
a la luna
que cuelga por el cielo
brillando en el mar y el hielo
-Maddie Miller
The beach
is a house
at the moon
that hangs in the sky
shining on the moon and the ice

Mi perro, eres una bebe
Mi perro, te ves como la nieve
Mi perro, me hace sonrisa
Mi perro, me da risa
Abbey Naso

My dog you are a baby
My dog you look like snow
My dog you make me smile
My dog you make me laugh

post_text:
Everyone is Invited!

2019 Distinguished Scholars Exhibition

Monday, April 15
Grosse Ile Middle School Auditeria
6:30PM-8:00PM

Students will have their Distinguished Scholar Projects on display and be prepared to answer questions about their learning process from the beginning of the project to its current stage. The event will be hosted in the Middle School Auditeria open house style. So, feel free to come, look around and inquire about these student-driven projects.

If you have any questions, please contact: Audrey Schmittou – schmita@gischools.org
